66  Thirdly, in this case (as in R (Carson) v Secretary of State for Work and Pensions 
		[2005] UKHL 37
	      ; 
		[2006] 1 AC 173
	      ) there is an objective justification for the different treatment of the two groups to which the appellant points. The two groups are asylum seekers and British citizens in need of social assistance. Asylum seekers are a large group of people, an unknown proportion of whom have no entitlement to be here. Their entitlement to welfare support derives from international instruments, which do not apply to British citizens. In this sphere it is for the legislature and the executive to determine how national resources should be allocated.”
